Shadowmere is the founding case for Kiess's Three-Power Governance. The Prism Archive treats it as the primary precedent for why separation of emergency powers exists. The sentence "Emergency powers without sunset are poison" is carved into the Prism's eastern face and read at every founding anniversary.

Midgaard founded Shadowmere as a frontier march-town. The Plague Mandate granted unchecked emergency authority. No rollback occurred. The Last Bell Crisis produced three contradictory decrees in one night. The city collapsed into five competing factions, all claiming legal authority.

Every element of Three-Power Governance was designed as a direct countermeasure to Shadowmere's failure modes. Compact Temples hold sanctuary law but cannot issue quarantine orders -- preventing rite-deadlock. Trade Syndics hold market authority but cannot conscript or seize without Wall Command countersignature -- preventing requisition spirals. Wall Command holds gate discipline but cannot extend emergency powers beyond one lunar cycle without Syndic and Temple renewal -- preventing permanent emergency states.

The founding charter's core principle: "No sealed warrant from a predecessor authority shall bind a Kiess citizen." This exists because Shadowmere's factions still enforce predecessor warrants centuries later.

Shadowmere's five factions represent five failure modes Kiess was built to prevent: the soldier who cannot stop (Oathbound March), the noble who cannot yield (Crimson Household), the clerk who cannot feel (Binder Collegium), the executioner who cannot rest (Gallows Syndicate), the survivor who cannot return (Fen-Adapted Remnants).

