Shadowmere is studied by Mafdet's Harbor Wardens as an institutional failure case. Its founding mandate -- guard transit, tax goods, process the dead, keep records -- mirrors functions Mafdet performs daily. Shadowmere could have been a peer city.

The Plague Mandate granted emergency powers with no review mechanism. In Mafdet, emergency harbor closures require Strandline Compact review within ten days. The chain can be raised under threat but must be lowered under attestation: a sworn statement reviewed by all three blocs. No single authority retains emergency powers beyond the emergency.

Shadowmere had no such constraint. Four power blocs deadlocked. The Last Bell Crisis -- three contradictory decrees in one night -- is the exact failure mode prevented by Mafdet's Dual-Attestation Protocol. Two independent verifications required; contradictions halt all action until reconciled. One authority issuing unchecked orders is how ports become prisons.

Blight Hydrology parallels harbor contamination doctrine. Runoff through burial districts, flooded crypts, toxic wetlands. The Quarantine Ledger classifies this as waste becoming environmental hazard. Mafdet maintains strict separation between ballast discharge, cargo handling, and healing-house drainage because contamination travels through infrastructure.

Five factions represent five forms of broken attestation: Oathbound March (unverified military orders), Crimson Household (unattested bloodline claims), Binder Collegium (unchecked clerical authority), Gallows Syndicate (monetized sentencing), Fen-Adapted Remnants (governance vacancy). The Shrine of the First Claw would recognize none of their oaths.

The Harbor Wardens' summary is carved above the chain house gate: "Orders stamped, witnessed, sealed, and wrong." It is the oldest entry in Mafdet's failure study collection.
